SIMPLE: labile
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Labile
<hw>La"bile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>labilis</ets>
apt to slip, fr. <ets>labi</ets> to slip.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Liable
to slip, err, fall, or apostatize.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Cheyne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Liable or likely to change.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Easily decomposed or inactivated
when subjected to heat, radiation, or mildly acidic or alkaline
conditions; -- of chemical compounds; <as>as, enzymes from thermophilic
organisms are not as <ex>labile</ex> as those from
mesophiles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lability</ent>⟦br⟧
